			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Kiting...<a name="27761"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Mar 15 04 11:17 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>The Orcish Lute is secondary. <a target="_new" href="http://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/item.html?item=16268">http://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/item.html?item=16268</a>
<br />

<br />
A lot of suggestions require you to buy an expensive item - so I'm assuming these come from long time players. I just started EQ about 6 weeks ago. I am now lvl 48 and should be done AoE kiting in a couple days when I hit 50. I kited LOIO, then Cougars, and now Spirocs. Here is my advice.
<br />

<br />
1. Know the speed of what you are kiting. Goblins, Sarnaks and Bones in LOIO run slower than your normal run speed - you don't need any acceleration to kite them. Sabertooths can be kited effectively with Selos(no drum), are very social for aggro and never run - but they are usually mixed in with a lot of other things that run slower and you really shouldn't mix run speeds in your kite. Cougars and Spirocs run just slower than SOW speed. You can Selos without a drum or just buy SOW potions. 10 dose potions can be found fairly cheaply and I never had a problem making more pp than I used in potions (cougars drops sell well and Spirocs drop pp, words, dust-15p per stack to a vendor). The SOW potion is real handy for when you get stunned - nothing worse than getting control back and finding Selos dropped.
<br />

<br />
2. You need to run tight circles for most AoE kites at speed. It has been mention elsewhere to autocircle(hit both up and left or right keys at same time then enter for cursor and enter again to be able to twist) but I like to hit autorun and just work the turn key to adjust my distance to the kite. You will get hit from time to time but it shouldn't be often and most things you kite stun - so it can be deadly. You dont need to run tight circles for slow LOIO mobs - nice lazy ones with sharp turns hit just when your song starts should do it.
<br />

<br />
3. Before 48 - just equip your brass (get the combine horn - cheap effective) and twist COD and DDD. If you have the pp you can buy a Lute of the Howler and Flawless Ivory Horn. Troub mace is fine but the drop off in damage for DDD is significant (Combine does 50% more). With just a horn it takes me about 15 mins to kit down 20+ Spirocs (per kite - 9-10 blue bars xp at lvl 38- 5 blue bars at lvl 47). Since Im now 48 Ill twist in my new AoE and just use my Orcish Lute.
<br />

<br />
4. While gathering up your kite, target the highest conning mob and use this mobs health to tell how well you are doing. You wont be landing every single song on every single mob, but picking one tough one from a crowd is usually a good indicator. 
<br />

<br />
5. Start small and work your way up. Try 4 mobs, then 8 mobs etc. Some say go for as many as you can until you get visual pathing errors - just remember - you lag you die. There is no reason to over do it just for braggin rights - you are a bard - you will already have braggin rights. I did the cougars in 2 kites rather than one - one on the gnome island then one on the island south. 1 Sow lasted for both and there was never any down time - one island repops when I finish the kite of the other. The only thing kiting everything at once will get you is more down time ... ok maybe more lag deaths too.
<br />

<br />
Just my 2 cp.
<br />

<br />
Have fun.</span></td>
